ERASMVS ROTERODAMVS MARCO LAVRINO SVO S. D.

Accam literas tuas, imo meros amores3 quid enim aliud sonant, quid aliud spirant? Mihi vero non minus in votis fuit frui con- suetudine tua quam tibi mea: id, vti spero, nunc quoque licebit. De conuiciis obtrectatorum qui omnibus arrosis nunc tandem in inconstantiam meam cauillantur, risi, fateor, vtpote iam assuetus .-·> istiusmodi blateramenffis, sed tamen risum ex parte sardonium. Nam mihi quidem aduersus istorum calumnias sufficeret animus bene sibi conscius. Caeterum quis non moleste ferat obstinatam ac peruersam hominum ingratitudinem? Nulli magis indigent meis laboribus quam isti qui sic oblatrant meis studiis, suis commodis. Nec vlli 10 oblatrant ferocius aut immanius quam ii qui libri nec operimentum vnquam viderunt. 808. 26. Siburgum] John LairofSieg· burg, 15 miles sn. of Cologne, usually known as Siberch ; the founder of the first Cambridge press. It is thought that by May 1520, when Cervicornus (Ep. 802. 8 n.) printed for him Croke⁷s Greek grammar, he was already settled at Cambridge as a bookseller and binder. In Feb. 1521 the first book appeared from his prese, and nine books printed by him in 1521-2 are known ; including two by Erasmus, the De conscribendis epistolis, from a copy of the original

draft (Ep.71). and the De Constructione- (Ep. 341). In 1525 Erasmus sends greetings to him through Aldridge (Lond. xxi. 26, LB. 782; cf. EE.2 40). There are entries relating to him in the University records as late as 1553; from which it appears that he entered the Church. See DN B 3 G. J. Gray, Gambridqe Stationem, pp. 54-61; and E. G. Duff, Centum of the Enylislz Boolc Trade, pp. 147—8.
